    value: 樓閣
english:
  title: 'Night Sitting at Cheongsim Pavilion on Yangsan: A Record of What I Observed'
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Wind shatters through the bamboo grove,
    Moon's shadow wavers on the orchid bank.
    A traveler, sleepless in autumn,
    Opens the window and wraps himself in soft robes.

    In the dimness, blossoms drift to distant fields,
    And the vital breath of heaven rises like waves.
    A leaping fish suddenly splashes—
    Startled, a crane cries out in full voice.

    Stars reflect on the crystalline green water,
    Where a pair of small boats drift across.
    Following the path to gaze at the tower,
    It rises solitary, piercing the sky.

    Where servants once struck the ground at dawn,
    Now only crickets sing their autumn song.
    Suddenly I feel the night breeze turn cool,
    And loosening my hair, I find sweet ease.

    But I fear the rooster's early call—
    Again I must don cap and sash,
    And hurry into the dusty world of duties.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Cheongsim Pavilion (澄心軒): ''Clear Mind Pavilion,'' suggesting a place of contemplative retreat.'
  - key: ''
    value: The work captures the tension between the peace of solitary night observation and the duties that await with dawn—a common theme in Korean literati poetry.
